definition.value: A proanthocyanidin obtained by the condensation of (-)-epicatechin units.
A gamma-amino acid that is GABA in which one of the hydrogens at position 4 is replaced by a cyano group.
The hydroxamate of phosphoglycolic acid.
A tolualdehyde compound with the methyl substituent at the 3-position.

A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 2-hydroxyphenyl group. It is a metabolite of phenylalanine and is excreted in the urine of patients suffering from diseases like phenylketonuria.
An optically active form of tyrosine having D-configuration.
A tricyclic sesquiterpene lactone found in wormwood.
An L-lyxose in open-chain aldehyde form.
The open-chain aldehydo-form of L-iduronic acid.
A member of the class of acetamides that is acetamide comprising histamine having an acetyl group attached to the side-chain amino function.
A C5, branched-chain saturated fatty acid.
An alkaloid found in the roots of Rauwolfia serpentina and R. vomitoria.
A xylene carrying methyl groups at positions 1 and 3.
An organochlorine compound that is maleylacetic acid substituted by a chloro group at position 2.
A methionine sulfoximine in which the amino group has S-stereochemistry.
A sulfated glycosaminoglycan comprising heparin glucosamine that is randomly sulfated at position 3.
A medium-chain fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of decanoic acid.
A phosphatidylglycerol composed of two molecules of phosphatidic acid covalently linked to a molecule of glycerol.
A tripeptoid arising from cleavage of both rings of a penicillin derivative.
An N-acetyl-D-galactosamine having beta-configuration at the anomeric centre.

A 1-ribosylimidazolecarboxamide in which the carboxamide group is situated at position 4 of the imidazole ring, which is further substituted at position 5 by an amino group. A purine nucleoside analogue and activator of AMP-activated protein kinase, it is  is used for the treatment of acute lymphoblastic leukemia and is reported to have cardioprotective effects.

A tetrahydroxyflavone in which the four hydroxy groups are located at positions 3, 5, 7 and 4'. Acting as an antioxidant by reducing oxidative stress, it is currently under consideration as a possible cancer treatment.
A member of the class of imidazoles that is 4,5-dihydro-1H-imidazole substituted by a benzyl group.
A cardenolide glycoside that is gitoxigenin in which the 3beta-hydroxy group has been glycosylated with tridigitoxose.
An organoarsonic acid that is methylarsonic acid in which one of the hydrogens of the methyl group is replaced by a carboxy group.
A cytidine phosphate compound having the phosphate group at the 2'-position.
A dihydroxybenzaldehyde carrying hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 5.
A monohaloethene that is ethene in which one of the hydrogens has been replaced by a chloro group.
An anthocyanidin chloride that has pelargonidin as the cationic counterpart.
A dTDP-sugar having 3,4-didehydro-2,6-dideoxy-D-glucose as the sugar component.
A Se-methylselenomethionine that has L-configuration.

An N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl glycopeptide consisting of an N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetylmuramoyl moiety attached to the amino terminus of the tripeptide L-alanyl-D-glutamyl-6-carboxy-L-lysine via an amide linkage.
A monocarboxylic acid amide of acetoacetic acid.
A member of the class of naphthalenediols that is 1,2-dihydronaphthalene substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 2 respectively.
